    <title>Combined summary - Continuing the discussion about noinput / anyprevout</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T21:38:18.075952+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-October/017333.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is discussing the potential risks and benefits of using different types of signatures, such as SIGHASH_NOINPUT and chaperone signatures, in off-chain protocols like Lightning. While these signatures can improve security and efficiency, they also introduce complexity for key management and may lead to fund loss if not used correctly. Developers are proposing different solutions, including BIP-118 and bip-anyprevout, to allow rebinding of transactions to new outputs while addressing these concerns. However, there remain open questions about the usefulness and safety of these proposals beyond eltoo, as well as support or opposition to chaperone signatures and output tagging.The Bitcoin development community has been discussing various proposals, including NOINPUT/ANYPREVOUT/ANYPREVOUTANANYSCRIPT and output tagging/explicit opt-in for transaction malleability. While there is general agreement on the adoption of these proposals to make better off-chain protocol designs, concerns have been raised about the potential misuse of NOINPUT by bad wallet designers. Additionally, the advantages and disadvantages of chaperone signatures and output tagging are also discussed. Finally, proposals for Decker-Russell-Osuntokun (DRO) and eltoo, two off-chain payment channel constructions for Bitcoin's Lightning Network, have been discussed.In a Bitcoin developers' mailing list, the proposal of output tagging as a solution for transaction malleability was discussed. The email thread discusses the usefulness of noinput, anyprevoutanyscript and anyprevout. ZmnSCPxj proposed the creation of a new opcode, `OP_CHECKSIG_WITHOUT_INPUT`, which would ignore any `SIGHASH` flags present on a signature. Bitcoin's SIGHASH_NOINPUT presents an issue of address reuse, which is common practice among bitcoin businesses. A proposal to change the allocation of SegWit v16 for SIGHASH_NOINPUT use, as well as a suggestion for an alternative solution has been made in the bitcoin-dev mailing list.In a Bitcoin development discussion, the idea of creating a new opcode called `OP_CHECKSIG_WITHOUT_INPUT` was proposed as an alternative to `SIGHASH_NOINPUT`. However, it was pointed out that there wouldn't be any meaningful difference between creating a new opcode and making a new tapscript public key type. The proposed new opcode would ignore any `SIGHASH` flags on a signature if present. Anthony Towns discussed the potential risks associated with anyprevout signatures in Bitcoin transactions. He noted that such signatures could make the address being signed for less safe, potentially resulting in loss of funds if additional coins are sent to the same address. The context discusses various proposals and discussions related to the Bitcoin protocol, including the use of SIGHASH_NOINPUT, concerns about address reuse, and the potential risks associated with anyprevout signatures. While these proposals are seen as useful for off-chain protocols like Lightning, there are concerns about potential misuse by bad wallet designers. The writer suggests that fixing footguns in the Bitcoin protocol is necessary, but it is important to keep on-chain hot wallet signing procedures separate from off-chain hot wallet signing procedures, which introduces more complexity for key management. Additionally, the advantages and disadvantages of chaperone signatures and output tagging/explicit opt-in are discussed.The Bitcoin development mailing list has seen discussions around several proposals, including Taproot and Decker-Russell-Osuntokun (DRO), which aim to improve off-chain protocol designs for Bitcoin's Lightning Network. The implementation of these proposals has been a topic of debate, with concerns raised about the potential misuse of no_input signatures, chaperone signatures, and output tagging/explicit opt-in. While there is general agreement on the adoption of these proposals, it is suggested that any extra code/tagging/whatever should be tested on a public testnet before being implemented in real-world settings. Additionally, maintaining key hygiene is essential to contain fund loss to the balance of the channel.Finally, discussions around rebinding transactions to new outputs have raised concerns about the security of no_input signatures, especially if multi-party transactions are involved. Richard Myers supports the unification and adoption of the sighash_noinput and anyprevoutput* proposals to enable eltoo, but also to make possible better off-chain protocol designs generally. Some developers propose new opcodes like OP_CHECKSIG_WITHOUT_INPUT as alternatives to SIGHASH_NOINPUT, but this may lead to increased design space and potential issues. The Bitcoin community is actively working to find the best solutions for improving the protocol's functionality while minimizing risk.</summary>
